    "---\n",
    "## 1. Focal Loss: Derivation from First Principles\n",
    "\n",
    "### 1.1 Binary Cross-Entropy Baseline\n",
    "\n",
    "For a binary classification problem with prediction $p \\in (0,1)$ and ground truth $y \\in \\{0,1\\}$:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\mathcal{L}_{BCE}(p, y) = -[y \\log p + (1-y)\\log(1-p)]$$\n",
    "\n",
    "**Gradient wrt pre-activation logit $z$ (where $p = \\sigma(z) = \\frac{1}{1+e^{-z}}$):**\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\frac{\\partial \\mathcal{L}_{BCE}}{\\partial z} = -(y - p) = p - y$$\n",
    "\n",
    "This gradient has magnitude $|p - y|$, which is small for well-classified examples — no focusing.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 1.2 Focal Loss Construction\n",
    "\n",
    "Define $p_t = p \\cdot \\mathbb{1}[y=1] + (1-p) \\cdot \\mathbb{1}[y=0]$ (correct-class probability).\n",
    "\n",
    "Focal Loss adds modulating factor $(1 - p_t)^\\gamma$:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\mathcal{L}_{FL}(p_t) = -(1-p_t)^\\gamma \\log p_t$$\n",
    "\n",
    "### 1.3 Gradient of Focal Loss wrt Logit $z$\n",
    "\n",
    "For the positive class ($y=1$), $p_t = p = \\sigma(z)$:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\frac{\\partial \\mathcal{L}_{FL}}{\\partial z} = \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial z}\\left[-(1-p)^\\gamma \\log p\\right]$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Using the chain rule and $\\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial z} = p(1-p)$:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$= -(1-p)^\\gamma \\cdot \\frac{1}{p} \\cdot p(1-p) + \\gamma(1-p)^{\\gamma-1} \\cdot p(1-p) \\cdot \\log p$$\n",
    "\n",
    "$$= -(1-p)^\\gamma(1-p) + \\gamma(1-p)^{\\gamma-1} p(1-p) \\log p$$\n",
    "\n",
    "$$= (1-p)^{\\gamma-1}\\left[-(1-p)^2 + \\gamma p (1-p) \\log p\\right]$$\n",
    "\n",
    "**Key insight:** For well-classified positives ($p \\to 1$), $(1-p)^{\\gamma-1} \\to 0$,\n",
    "suppressing the gradient. At $\\gamma=2$:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\frac{\\partial \\mathcal{L}_{FL}}{\\partial z}\\bigg|_{p=0.95} \\approx 0.0025 \\cdot (-0.0025 + \\ldots) \\ll 1$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Compared to BCE gradient at same point: $p - y = 0.95 - 1 = -0.05$. Focal loss reduces this by **20×**.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 1.4 Why Focal Loss Matters for Dense Detection\n",
    "\n",
    "In a typical dense detection scenario with $B = 100,000$ anchor boxes per image:\n",
    "- ~99,900 are easy negatives (background)\n",
    "- ~100 are positives (objects)\n",
    "\n",
    "With BCE, easy negatives dominate the loss by a factor of **999:1** even if each contributes\n",
    "only $0.01$ loss. Focal Loss ($\\gamma=2$) reduces easy negative contribution by up to $10,000\\times$."
   ]
  },
