    "---\n",
    "## 3. Batch Normalisation: Distribution Shift Analysis\n",
    "\n",
    "### 3.1 The Internal Covariate Shift Problem\n",
    "\n",
    "As weights update during training, the distribution of inputs to each layer changes —\n",
    "this is the **internal covariate shift** (Ioffe & Szegedy, 2015). Formally, if $h_{l-1}$ has\n",
    "distribution $p_l(h)$ at step $t$, at step $t+1$ it changes to $p_{l}^{(t+1)}(h)$.\n",
    "\n",
    "Each layer must constantly adapt to new input statistics, slowing learning.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 3.2 Batch Normalisation Formulation\n",
    "\n",
    "For a mini-batch $\\mathcal{B} = \\{x_1, \\ldots, x_m\\}$:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\mu_\\mathcal{B} = \\frac{1}{m}\\sum_{i=1}^m x_i, \\quad\n",
    "\\sigma_\\mathcal{B}^2 = \\frac{1}{m}\\sum_{i=1}^m (x_i - \\mu_\\mathcal{B})^2$$\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\hat{x}_i = \\frac{x_i - \\mu_\\mathcal{B}}{\\sqrt{\\sigma_\\mathcal{B}^2 + \\epsilon}}, \\quad\n",
    "y_i = \\gamma\\hat{x}_i + \\beta$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The learnable parameters $\\gamma$ (scale) and $\\beta$ (shift) restore the representational\n",
    "capacity that normalisation would otherwise remove.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 3.3 Gradient of Batch Norm (Full Derivation)\n",
    "\n",
    "Given downstream loss gradient $\\frac{\\partial \\mathcal{L}}{\\partial y_i}$:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\frac{\\partial \\mathcal{L}}{\\partial \\gamma} = \\sum_i \\frac{\\partial \\mathcal{L}}{\\partial y_i}\\hat{x}_i, \\quad\n",
    "\\frac{\\partial \\mathcal{L}}{\\partial \\beta} = \\sum_i \\frac{\\partial \\mathcal{L}}{\\partial y_i}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\frac{\\partial \\mathcal{L}}{\\partial x_i} = \\frac{\\gamma}{m\\sigma_\\mathcal{B}}\n",
    "\\left(m\\frac{\\partial \\mathcal{L}}{\\partial y_i} - \\sum_j\\frac{\\partial \\mathcal{L}}{\\partial y_j}\n",
    "- \\hat{x}_i\\sum_j\\frac{\\partial \\mathcal{L}}{\\partial y_j}\\hat{x}_j\\right)$$\n",
    "\n",
    "### 3.4 Implications for Dense Object Detection\n",
    "\n",
    "In retail shelf images, batch statistics vary significantly between:\n",
    "- Dense-region patches (high activation variance)\n",
    "- Sparse-region patches (lower activation variance)\n",
    "\n",
    "This is why **Group Normalisation** or **Layer Normalisation** can outperform Batch Norm\n",
    "in small-batch object detection (Detectron2 uses GN by default for Mask R-CNN).\n",
    "DCAM's density map conditioning implicitly addresses this by providing explicit density\n",
    "information that BN statistics alone cannot capture."
   ]
