    "---\n",
    "## 4. Loss Landscape Geometry\n",
    "\n",
    "### 4.1 Loss Landscape Characterisation\n",
    "\n",
    "The loss landscape $\\mathcal{L}(\\theta)$ of a neural network is a high-dimensional\n",
    "non-convex surface. Key geometric properties:\n",
    "\n",
    "**1. Saddle Points dominate in high dimensions.**\n",
    "For a point $\\theta^*$ where $\\nabla \\mathcal{L} = 0$, the Hessian $H$ has both positive\n",
    "and negative eigenvalues. In $d$ dimensions, the probability of a critical point being a\n",
    "local minimum decreases as $O(e^{-d})$ (Dauphin et al., 2014).\n",
    "\n",
    "**2. SGD escapes saddle points efficiently.**\n",
    "Gradient noise from mini-batches provides stochasticity that helps escape saddle points.\n",
    "The effective Hessian of the SGD noise covariance is $C = \\eta \\cdot H / B$ where\n",
    "$\\eta$ is the learning rate and $B$ is the batch size.\n",
    "\n",
    "**3. Wide minima generalise better.**\n",
    "A minimum with small Hessian eigenvalues (flat landscape) has a large $\\epsilon$-neighbourhood\n",
    "within a given loss value, making it robust to parameter perturbations (and thus to test data\n",
    "distribution shifts).\n",
    "\n",
    "**4. Implications for our optimiser choice (AdamW):**\n",
    "AdamW = Adam + weight decay (L2 regularisation applied to gradient, not to the update step).\n",
    "This encourages movement toward flat minima by penalising large parameter norms,\n",
    "which corresponds geometrically to preferring minima in low-curvature regions.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 4.2 Warmup + Cosine Annealing Schedule\n",
    "\n",
    "Our LR schedule: linear warmup for $T_w$ steps, then cosine annealing:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\eta_t = \\begin{cases}\n",
    "\\eta_{max} \\cdot t / T_w & t < T_w \\\\\n",
    "\\eta_{min} + \\frac{1}{2}(\\eta_{max} - \\eta_{min})\\left(1 + \\cos\\frac{\\pi(t-T_w)}{T - T_w}\\right) & t \\geq T_w\n",
    "\\end{cases}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Warmup prevents large gradient updates at the start (when the loss surface is steep).\n",
    "Cosine annealing gradually reduces the effective temperature, allowing settlement into\n",
    "a flat minimum without oscillation."
   ]
